newsitem.title: USA: US late Midco prods jump, but gasoline diffs ease.
newsitem.headline: US late Midco prods jump, but gasoline diffs ease.

text.p: U.S. spot products prices rose sharply on Midcontinent markets by late Wednesday tracking NYMEX futures, players said, although gasoline differentials eased with waning demand.

Inventory reports, showing disappointing distillate inventory builds, were cited as the fuel for the rally. Most distillate grades firmed by about two cents a gallon, while gasolines rose by about 0.75 cent.
The API report showed a 766,000 barrel build in low sulphur diesel supplies in the midwest last week. It showed gasoline stocks falling by 791,000 barrels.
But gasoline diffs slipped with shrinking demand, with Chicago prompt unleaded easing 0.75 cent since Tuesday to a half cent under the print, players said.
"As soon as the weather turn colder, gasoline demand goes way down," explained one trader, noting that temperatures have been dipping in certain areas in the midwest this week.
Group Three unleaded gasoline was pegged at 0.60 cent under the October print for prompt barrels.
Prompt low sulphur diesel was bid 2.50 cents over the print in Group Three and 1.25 cents over in Chicago, with high sulphur steady in both markets.
